A075001.name: Smallest k such that the concatenation of n consecutive numbers starting with k (from k to n+k-1) is a multiple of n; or 0 if no such number exists.

A075002.name: a(n) = smallest k such that A007908(k) is divisible by n.

A075003.name: Floor[ concatenation of n+1 and n divided by 2 ].

A075004.name: Floor[ concatenation of n+2, n+1 and n divided by 3 ].

A075005.name: Floor[ concatenation of n+3, n+2, n+1 and n divided by 4 ].

A075006.name: Floor[ concatenation of n+4, n+3, n+2, n+1 and n divided by 5].

A075007.name: Floor[ concatenation of n+5, n+4,n+3, n+2, n+1 and n divided by 6].

A075008.name: Floor[ concatenation of 7 numbers from n+6 to n in that order divided by 7].

A075009.name: Floor[ concatenation of 8 numbers from n+7 to n in that order divided by 8].

A075010.name: a(n) = floor( concatenation of 9 numbers from n+8 to n in that order divided by 9 ).

A075011.name: Floor[ concatenation of numbers from n to 1 divided by concatenation of numbers from 1 to n].

A075013.name: Smallest k such that the decimal concatenation of k and k+1 is divisible by n.

A075014.name: Smallest k such that the concatenation k, k-1 is divisible by n; or 0 if no such number exists.

A075015.name: Smallest k such that the concatenation k, k+1, k+2 is divisible by n; or 0 if no such number exists.

A075016.name: Smallest k such that the concatenation k, k-1,k-2 is divisible by n; or 0 if no such number exists.

A075017.name: Smallest k such that the concatenation k, k+1,k+2,k+3 is divisible by n; or 0 if no such number exists.

A075018.name: Smallest k such that the concatenation k, k-1,k-2,k-3 is divisible by n; or 0 if no such number exists.

A075019.name: a(1) = 1; for n > 1, a(n) = the smallest prime divisor of the number C(n) formed from the concatenation of 1,2,3,... up to n.

A075020.name: a(1) = 1; for n>1, a(n) = the smallest prime divisor of the number C(n) formed from the reverse concatenation of 1,2,3,... up to n.

A075021.name: a(1) = 1; for n>1, a(n) = the largest prime divisor of the number C(n) formed from the reverse concatenation of 1,2,3,... up to n.

A075022.name: a(1) = 1; for n>1, a(n) = the largest prime divisor of the number C(n) formed from the concatenation of 1,2,3,... up to n.

A075023.name: a(n) = the smallest prime divisor of A173426(n) = concatenation of (1, 2, 3,..., n, n-1, ..., 1) for n > 1; a(1) = 1.

A075024.name: a(n) = the largest prime divisor of the number A173426(n) = concatenate(1,2,...,n-1,n,n-1,...,2,1) .
formula: a(n) = A006530(A173426(n)). - _Michel Marcus_, Jun 05 2014, corrected by _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 29 2015

A075025.name: Numbers n such that d(n) < d(n-1) and d(n) < d(n+1), where d(k) is the number of divisors of k.

A075026.name: Define a number k to occupy a divisor cavity if d(k-1) > d(k) < d(k+1) where d(k) is the number of divisors of k. Sequence gives composite numbers occupying a divisor cavity.

A075027.name: Define a number k to occupy a divisor pole if d(k-1) < d(k) > d(k+1) where d(k) is the number of divisors of k. Sequence gives numbers occupying a divisor pole.

A075028.name: a(1) = 1, then a(n) = the smallest number k such that the number of divisors of the n numbers from k through k+n-1 are in strictly ascending order.

A075029.name: Smallest initial number k of n consecutive numbers satisfying numdiv(k) > numdiv(k+1) > ... > numdiv(k+n-1).

A075030.name: Primes for which the four closest primes are smaller.

A075031.name: a(n) is the smallest number k such that the number of divisors of the n numbers from k through k+n-1 are nonincreasing.

A075032.name: Numbers n such that tau(n) <= tau(n+1) <= tau(n+2) where tau(n) = number of divisors of n.

A075033.name: Numbers n such that tau(n) <= tau(n+1) <= tau(n+2) <= tau(n+3) where tau(n) = number of divisors of n.

A075034.name: Numbers n such that tau(n) >= tau(n+1) >= tau(n+2) where tau(n) = number of divisors of n.

A075035.name: Numbers n such that tau(n) >= tau(n+1) >= tau(n+2) >= tau(n+3) where tau(n) = number of divisors of n.

A075036.name: Smaller of two smallest consecutive numbers with 2n divisors.
formula: a(n) <= A215199(n-1) for n > 1. Conjecture: if p is prime, then a(p) = A215199(p-1). This conjecture is true if the conjecture in A215199 is true. The b-file of A215199 thus shows that a(p) = A215199(p-1) for prime p < 1279. - _Chai Wah Wu_, Mar 12 2019

A075037.name: Primes for which the five closest primes are smaller.

A075038.name: Primes for which the six closest primes are smaller.

A075039.name: Smallest of three consecutive squarefree numbers having equal numbers of prime factors.

A075040.name: a(1) = 0; a(n) = smallest of three consecutive numbers all with 2n divisors.

A075043.name: Primes for which the seven closest primes are smaller.

A075044.name: a(0) = 1; a(n) = the smallest number k such that n numbers from k to k+n-1 have n distinct prime divisors, or 0 if no such number exists.

A075045.name: Coefficients A_n for the s=3 tennis ball problem.
formula: G.f.: seems to be (3*g-1)^(-2)*(1-g)^(-3) where g*(1-g)^2 = x. - _Mark van Hoeij_, Nov 10 2011

A075046.name: a(n) = the smallest number k such that the number of divisors of the n numbers from k through k+n-1 are in (nonstrictly) ascending order.

A075047.name: Numbers k whose prime factorization contains the same digits as k.

A075048.name: 10-smooth numbers that show their prime factors.

A075049.name: n is in the sequence if every digit of n is a divisor of n and every divisor of n in the range [2,9] occurs at least once as a digit of n.

A075050.name: Primes for which the eight closest primes are smaller.

A075051.name: Smallest prime for which the n closest primes are smaller.

A075052.name: Write down squares and cubes in order, as in A002760. The sequence gives the first differences between terms.

A075053.name: Number of primes (counted with repetition) that can be formed by rearranging some or all of the digits of n.
formula: a(n) >= A039993(n) with equality iff n has no duplicate digit. -  _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 14 2019

a(n) = Sum_{k in S(n)} A039999(k), if n has not more than one digit 0, where S(n) are the numbers whose nonzero digits are a subsequence of those of n, and which contain the digit 0 if n does, taken with multiplicity (for numbers using some but not all digits that are repeated in n). - _M. F. Hasler_, Oct 15 2019

A075054.name: Smallest k such that (n+1)(n+2)...(n+k) is divisible by n!.

A075055.name: Smallest integer of the form product (n+1)(n+2)...(n+k)/n!.

A075056.name: a(1) = 0, then smallest square such that a(n+1)- a(n) is a palindrome.

A075057.name: a(1) = 0, then smallest triangular number such that a(n+1)- a(n) is a palindrome.

A075058.name: 1 followed by the greatest primes selected to form a complete sequence (see algorithm below).
formula: a(n) ~ k*2^n, with k roughly 0.748643. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Apr 05 2013

A075060.name: a(n) = solution to the postage stamp problem with n denominations and 10 stamps.

A075061.name: Triangle in A075059 read by rows.

A075062.name: Row sums of triangle in A075059.

A075063.name: Smallest prime == 1 mod first n composite numbers.

A075064.name: Smallest composite number == 1 mod first n prime numbers.

A075065.name: a(1) = 1 and then alternately even and odd composite numbers matching the parity of the index.

A075066.name: Alternately odd and even composite numbers complementing the parity of the index.

A075067.name: Start of the first run of exactly n consecutive odd composite numbers.

A075068.name: Product of p(n) primes starting from p(n).

A075069.name: Product of prime(n) consecutive numbers starting from prime(n).

A075070.name: a(n) = n-th compositorial number / (product of those primes which divide the n-th compositorial number).

A075071.name: n! divided by product of factorials of all proper divisors of n, as n runs through the values for which the result is an integer.

A075072.name: a(1) = 1; for n > 1, a(n) = n! divided by product of factorials of all prime divisors of n.

A075073.name: Numbers n such that n-th perfect power - n is prime: A001597(n) - n is prime.

A075074.name: Integers pertaining to A099520: a(n) = {b(n)+b(n+1)}/n where b(n) is the n-th term of A099520.

A075075.name: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2 and then the smallest number not occurring earlier such that every term divides the product of its neighbors: a(n-1)*a(n+1)/a(n) is an integer.

A075076.name: Integers pertaining to A075075: a(n) = b(n-1)*b(n+1)/b(n) where b(n) is the n-th term of A075075.

A075077.name: a(1) =1 and then the smallest number not occurring earlier such that a(n)+a(n+1) gives a different composite number (not obtained earlier).

A075078.name: Composite numbers which do not arise as a sum of two neighboring terms of A075077.

A075079.name: Numbers k in A001597 such that 2*k + 1 is prime.

A075081.name: Perfect powers q (A001597) such that (q-1)/2 is prime.

A075082.name: Numbers n such that n! is a product of distinct factorials k!*l!*m!*... with k, l, m, etc. < n.

A075083.name: Largest composite number formed by permuting the digits of n, or 0 if no such number exists.

A075084.name: Number of composite numbers between n and 2n.
formula: n - Pi(2n) + Pi(n-1) + 1. The sequence is nondecreasing.

A075085.name: a(n) is the smallest number not already in the sequence such that Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) is divisible by prime(n).

A075086.name: Rearrangement of natural numbers such that the n-th partial sum is divisible by the n-th composite number.

A075087.name: Rearrangement of natural numbers such that the n-th partial sum is divisible by the n-th squarefree number.

A075088.name: Smallest triangular number with n prime factors (counted with multiplicity).

A075089.name: Smallest prime == 1 mod n-th composite number.

A075091.name: Sum of Lucas numbers and reflected Lucas numbers (comment to A061084).

A075092.name: Sum of generalized tribonacci numbers (A001644) and reflected generalized tribonacci numbers (A073145).

A075093.name: Smallest member of Ormiston prime triple.

A075094.name: Triangle of the sorted orders of graph automorphism groups for the simple graphs.

A075095.name: Number of simple graphs g on n nodes with |Aut(g)| = 2.

A075096.name: Number of simple graphs g on n nodes with |Aut(g)| = 4.

A075097.name: Number of simple graphs g on n nodes with |Aut(g)| = 6.

A075098.name: Number of simple graphs g on n nodes with |Aut(g)| = 8.

A075099.name: Minimal total number of multiplications needed to generate all words of length n in the free monoid on two generators.

A075100.name: Number of terms of length < n that are needed on the way to computing all words of length n in the free monoid with two generators.

A075102.name: Number of steps to reach the first integer starting with 2^n/n and iterating the map x->x*ceiling(x), or -1 if no integer is ever reached.

A075104.name: Greatest common divisor of n and integer part of log_2(n).

A075105.name: Numerator of n/floor(log_2(n)); denominator is A075106(n).

A075106.name: Denominator of n/floor(log_2(n)); numerator is A075105(n).

A075107.name: Number of steps to reach the first integer (=A075108(n)) starting with n/floor(log_2(n)) and iterating the map x -> x*ceiling(x), or -1 if no integer is ever reached.

A075108.name: First integer reached when starting with n/floor(log_2(n)) and iterating the map x -> x*ceiling(x) A075107(n) times, or -1 if no integer is ever reached.

A075110.name: Concatenation of n-th prime and n in decimal notation.

A075111.name: a(n)=Sum((-1)^(i+Floor(n/2))T(2i+e),(i=0,..,Floor(n/2))), where T(n) are tribonacci numbers (A000073) and e=(1/2)(1-(-1)^n).

A075112.name: a(n)=Sum((-1)^(i+Floor(n/2))S(2i+e),(i=0,..,Floor(n/2))), where S(n) are generalized Tetranacci numbers (A073817) and e=(1/2)(1-(-1)^n).

A075114.name: Perfect powers n such that 2n + 1 is a perfect power; the value of y^b in the solution of the Diophantine equation x^a - 2y^b = 1.

A075117.name: Table by antidiagonals of generalized Lucas numbers: T(n,k) = T(n,k-1) + n*T(n,k-2) with T(n,0)=2 and T(n,1)=1.
formula: T(n, k) = 2^(1-k)*Sum_{j=0..floor(k/2)} binomial(k, 2*j)*(1+4*n)^j. - _G. C. Greubel_, Jan 27 2020

A075118.name: Variant on Lucas numbers: a(n) = a(n-1) + 3*a(n-2) with a(0)=2 and a(1)=1.
formula: a(n) = [x^n] ( (1 + x + sqrt(1 + 2*x + 13*x^2))/2 )^n for n >= 1. - _Peter Bala_, Jun 23 2015

A075119.name: Denominator of n/floor(sqrt(n)); numerator is A073890(n).

A075120.name: Number of steps to reach the first integer (= A075121(n)) starting with n/floor(sqrt(n)) and iterating the map x -> x*ceiling(x), or -1 if no integer is ever reached.

A075121.name: First integer reached when starting with n/floor(sqrt(n)) and iterating the map x -> x*ceiling(x) A075107(n) times, or -1 if no integer is ever reached.

A075122.name: a(n) = least positive integer > a(n-1) and not a(i)+2*a(j) for 1<=i<j<n.

A075123.name: a(n) is the least positive integer > a(n-1) and a(n) is not 2*a(i)+a(j) for 1<=i<j<n.
formula: a(n) = 4n - 10 - (n mod 2), for n>3. - _Ralf Stephan_, Nov 16 2004
a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2) - a(n-3) for n > 3. - _Harvey P. Dale_, Oct 28 2012

A075124.name: Orders of symmetric, cubic, connected graphs, sorted from largest to smallest with duplications when there exist multiple such graphs of the same order.

A075125.name: Number of parallelogram polyominoes of site-perimeter n (also called staircase polyominoes, although that term is overused).
formula: a(n) ~ sqrt(2) * ((3+sqrt(5))/2)^n / (sqrt(377 + 843/sqrt(5)) * sqrt(Pi) * n^(3/2)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 21 2014

A075126.name: Number of bargraphs of site-perimeter n.
formula: The generating function is known in closed form. Closed, but complicated. It is proved to be non-D-finite.

A075127.name: Safe perfect powers: perfect powers n such that (n-1)/2 is also a perfect power.

A075128.name: Binomial transform of generalized tetranacci numbers A073817: a(n)=Sum((-1)^k Binomial(n,k)*A073817(k),(k=0,..,n)).

A075129.name: Binomial transform of reflected tetranacci numbers A074058: a(n)=Sum((-1)^k Binomial(n,k)*A074058(k),(k=0,..,n)).

A075131.name: Picture-perfect numbers of form 57*p for p in A075130. The decimal reversal is equal to the sum of the reversed proper divisors.

A075132.name: a(0)=1; for n > 0, a(n)=sum(binomial(n,k)*binomial(n+k,k+1)*binomial(n+k+1,k),k=0..n)/n.
formula: Special values of the hypergeometric function 3F2, in Maple notation: a(n)=hypergeom([ n+1, n+2, -n], [1, 2], -1)

A075133.name: Indices of double-safe primes: p=prime(n) is double-safe: q=(p-1)/2 & r=(q-1)/2 are both prime (and q is safe).

A075134.name: Indices of triple-safe primes: p=prime(n) is double-safe: q=(p-1)/2, r=(q-1)/2 and s=(r-1)/2 are all prime (and q is double-safe).

A075135.name: Numerator of the generalized harmonic number H(n,3,1) described below.

A075136.name: Numerator of the generalized harmonic number H(n,4,1).

A075137.name: Numerator of the generalized harmonic number H(n,5,1).

A075138.name: Denominator of the generalized harmonic number H(n,5,1).

A075139.name: Numerator of the generalized harmonic number H(n,5,2).

A075140.name: Denominator of the generalized harmonic number H(n,5,2).

A075141.name: Numerator of the generalized harmonic number H(n,5,3).

A075142.name: Denominator of the generalized harmonic number H(n,5,3).

A075143.name: Numerator of the generalized harmonic number H(n,5,4).

A075144.name: Denominator of the generalized harmonic number H(n,5,4).

A075145.name: Prime basis of A061373.
formula: a(n)=A061373(A000040(n)), where p(n)=A000040(n) lists the primes. If p(n)-1 is written as product p(i)^e_i, then a(n) = 1 + sum a(i)*e_i.

A075146.name: n-th perfect power - n-th prime: pp(n) - prime(n).

A075147.name: Number of Lyndon words (aperiodic necklaces) with n beads of n colors.
formula: a(n) is the n-th term of the inverse Euler transform of j-> n^j. - _Alois P. Heinz_, Jun 23 2018
a(n) = [x^n] Sum_{k>=1} mu(k)*log(1/(1 - n*x^k))/k. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 20 2019

A075148.name: Table E(n,k) (listed antidiagonalwise as E(0,0), E(1,0), E(0,1), E(2,0), E(1,1), E(0,2), ...) where E(n,k) is F(n+k) for all even n and L(n+k) for all odd n. F(n) and L(n) are the n-th Fibonacci (A000045) and Lucas (A000032) numbers respectively.

A075149.name: Sum_{i=0..2*A053645(n)} (C(2*A053645(n),i) mod 2)*A000045(n-i) [where C(r,c) is the binomial coefficient (A007318) and A000045(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number).].

A075150.name: a(n)=L(n)*C(n), L(n)=Lucas numbers (A000032), C(n)=reflected Lucas numbers (see comment to A061084).

A075151.name: a(n)=L(n)^2*C(n), L(n)=Lucas numbers (A000032), C(n)=reflected Lucas numbers (comment to A061084).
formula: a(n) is asymptotic to (-phi)^(3n) where phi is the golden ratio (1+sqrt(5))/2. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Sep 07 2002

A075152.name: Number of possible permutations of a Rubik cube of size n X n X n.

A075153.name: Trajectory of 318 under the Reverse and Add! operation carried out in base 4, written in base 10.

A075154.name: a(n) is the smallest multiple of n such that a(n) mod 100 = n and S(n)=n where S(n) is the sum of the base-ten digits of n, or 0 if no such a(n) exists.

A075155.name: Cubes of Lucas numbers.
formula: a(n) = L(n)*C(n)^2, L(n) = Lucas numbers (A000032), C(n) = reflected Lucas numbers (comment to A061084).

A075156.name: Binomial transform of pentanacci numbers A074048: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k)*A074048(k).

A075157.name: Run lengths in the binary expansion of n gives the vector of exponents in prime factorization of a(n)+1, with the least significant run corresponding to the exponent of the least prime, 2; with one subtracted from each run length, except for the most significant run of 1's.

A075158.name: Prime factorization of n+1 encoded with the run lengths of binary expansion.

A075159.name: Run lengths in the binary expansion of n-1 gives the vector of exponents in prime factorization of a(n), with the least significant run corresponding to the exponent of the least prime, 2.

A075160.name: Prime factorization of n encoded with the run lengths of binary expansion + 1.

A075162.name: Position of A014486(n) in A075165, minus one.

A075163.name: Position of A075165(n) in A014486 plus one.

A075164.name: Position of A014486(n-1) in A075165.
formula: a(n) = A106443(A106454(n)). A000040(n) = a(1+A014137(n)). The powers of two are located at indices given by A057548 + 1, permuted by this same sequence, i.e. a(A057548(n)+1) = A000079(a(n)). - _Antti Karttunen_, May 09 2005

A075165.name: Sequence A075166 interpreted as binary numbers and converted to decimal.

A075166.name: Natural numbers mapped to Dyck path encodings of the rooted plane trees obtained by recursing on the exponents of the prime factorization of n.

A075167.name: Number of edges in each rooted plane tree produced with the unranking algorithm presented in A075166, which is based on prime factorization.
formula: For all n >= 2, a(n) = A055642(A075166(n))/2. [Half of the number of decimal digits in A075166(n).]
For all n >= 2, a(n) = A029837(1+A075165(n))/2. [Half of the binary width of A075165(n).]
For all n >= 1, a(n) = A000120(A075165(n)). [Thus also the binary weight of A075165(n), because half of the bits are zeros.]

A075170.name: Sequence A075171 interpreted as binary numbers and converted to decimal.

A075171.name: Nonnegative integers mapped to Dyck path encodings of the rooted plane trees obtained by recursing on the run lengths of the binary expansion of n.

A075172.name: Number of edges in each rooted plane tree produced with the binary run length unranking algorithm presented in A075171.

A075173.name: Prime factorization of n encoded by interleaving successive prime exponents in unary to bit-positions given by columns of A075300.

A075174.name: Inverse function of N -> N injection A075173.

A075175.name: Prime factorization of n encoded by interleaving successive prime exponents in unary to bit-positions given by columns of A001477.

A075176.name: Inverse function of N -> N injection A075175.

A075177.name: Indices of additive primes - primes with prime sum-of-digits, see A046704.

A075178.name: Denominators of expansion of 1/x+1/log(1-x).
formula: Denominators from e.g.f. 1/x + 1/log(1-x) (and of signed sequence from e.g.f. 1/x - 1/log(1+x)).
a(n) = denominator(r(n)), n>=0, with rational r(n) defined in one of the comments.

A075180.name: Denominators from e.g.f. 1/(1-exp(-x)) - 1/x.
formula: a(n) = denominator(-Zeta(-n)) = denominator(((-1)^(n+1))*B(n+1)/(n+1)), n >= 0, with Riemann's zeta function and the Bernoulli numbers B(n).
a(n) = denominators from e.g.f. (B(-x) - 1)/x, with B(x) = x/(exp(x) - 1), e.g.f. for Bernoulli numbers A027641(n)/A027642(n), n >= 0.

a(2n-1) = A006863(n)/2 for n > 0. By the comments in A006863, A006863(n) = A079612(2n) for n > 0. Hence a(n) = A079612(n+1)/2 all odd n. For all even n > 0, we have a(n) = 1, which is also equal to A079612(n+1)/2.
For odd n, a(n) is the product of p^(e+1) where p^e*(p-1) divides n+1 but p^(e+1)*(p-1) does not. For example, a(11) = 2^3 * 3^2 * 5^1 * 7^1 * 13^1 = 32760.

A075181.name: Coefficients of certain polynomials (rising powers).
formula: a(n, m) = (n-m)!*|S1(n, n-m)|, n>=m+1>=1, else 0, with S1(n, m) := A008275(n, m) (Stirling1).

A075182.name: Greatest common divisors of rows of triangle A075181 and of (unsigned) triangle A048594.

A075183.name: One half of third column of triangle A075181.

A075184.name: One half of fourth column of triangle A075181.

A075185.name: One-fourth of fifth column of triangle A075181.

A075186.name: Sixth column of triangle A075181 divided by 4!.

A075187.name: Seventh column of triangle A075181 divided by 4!.

A075188.name: Number of times that the numerator of a sum generated from the set 1, 1/2, 1/3,..., 1/n is prime.

A075189.name: Number of distinct primes in the numerator of the 2^n sums generated from the set 1, 1/2, 1/3, ..., 1/n.

A075190.name: Numbers k such that k^2 is an interprime = average of two successive primes.

A075191.name: Numbers k such that k^3 is an interprime = average of two successive primes.

A075192.name: Numbers k such that k^4 is an interprime = average of two successive primes.

A075193.name: Expansion of (1-2*x)/(1+x-x^2).
formula: a(n) = term (1,1) in the 1x2 matrix [1,-2] * [-1,1; 1,0]^n. - _Alois P. Heinz_, Jul 31 2008
a(n) = A186679(n)+A186679(n-2) for n>1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Feb 25 2011
E.g.f.: exp(-(1+sqrt(5))*x/2)*(3 + sqrt(5) - 2*exp(sqrt(5)*x))/(1 + sqrt(5)). - _Stefano Spezia_, Jan 12 2020

A075194.name: Binomial transform of pentanacci numbers A074048: a(n)=Sum((-1)^k*Binomial(n,k)*A074048(k),(k=0,..,n)).

A075195.name: Jablonski table T(n,k) read by antidiagonals: T(n,k) = number of necklaces with n beads of k colors.
formula: T(n,k) = (1/n)*Sum_{d | n} phi(d)*k^(n/d), where phi = Euler totient function A000010. - _Philippe Deléham_, Oct 08 2003
O.g.f. for column k >= 1: Sum_{n>=1} T(n,k)*x^n = -Sum_{d >= 1} (phi(d)/d) * log(1 - k*x^d).

Linear recurrence for row n >= 1: T(n,k) = Sum_{j=0..n} -binomial(j-n-1,j+1) * T(n,k-1-j) for k >= n + 2. (This recurrence is essentially due to _Robert A. Russell_, who contributed it in A321791.) (End)

A075833.name: Least k such that for any p prime dividing n, p does not divide binomial((n+1)*k, k+1) or 0 if no k was found.
formula: a(p^m) = p^m - 1 for prime p and m > 0. [Proof: if k in base p is x_1 x_2 ... x_t and t <= m, then (p^m+1)*k in base p is x_1 x_2 ... x_t 0 0 ... 0 x_1 x_2 ... x_t. Let k+1 in base p be y_1 y_2 ... y_r, where r = t or t+1. By Lucas theorem, we have y_r <= x_t, y_(r-1) <= x_(t-1), y_(r-2) <= x_(t-2), ... Therefore, x_1 = x_2 = ... = x_m = p-1 and k in base 10 is p^m - 1. - _Jinyuan Wang_, Apr 06 2020]

A075834.name: Coefficients of power series A(x) such that n-th term of A(x)^n = n! x^(n-1) for n > 0.
formula: G.f.: A(x) = x/series_reversion(x*G(x)); G(x) = A(x*G(x)); A(x) = G(x/A(x)); where G(x) is the g.f. of the factorials (A000142). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 09 2006
G.f.: A(x) = 1 + x*F(x) where F(x) satisfies F(x) = 1 + x*F(x) + x^2*F(x)*F'(x) and F'(x) = d/dx F(x). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Sep 02 2008
A003319(n+1) = coefficient of x^n in A(x)^n. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 23 2014

A075848.name: Numbers k such that 2*k^2 + 9 is a square.

formula: There is a fairly obvious pattern to these numbers.

formula: For n odd, a(n)=(n-1)^2/2+1. For n even, it is conjectured that a(n)=(n^2-n+2)/2 (it is easy to show this is a lower bound).

A075856.name: Triangle formed from coefficients of the polynomials p(1)=x, p(n+1) = (n + x*(n+1))*p(n) + x*x*(d/dx)p(n).
formula: T(n, k) = (n-1) * T(n-1, k) + (n+k-1) * T(n-1, k-1). - _Michael Somos_, Mar 17 2011
G.f. A(x, t) = Sum_{n>0} p[n] t^n / n! satisfies (dA / dt) * (x + t - 1) = x * (1 + A)^2 * (x * (1 + A) - 1). - _Michael Somos_, Mar 17 2011
This triangle is A185164 read by diagonals.
Let F(x) = x + (1-x)*log(1-x). The e.g.f. is given by the compositional inverse
Let f(x) = 1/log(1+x) and define inductively D^(n+1)(f(x)) = f(x)*(d/dx)(D^n(f(x))) with D^(0)f(x) = f(x). Then D^(n)f = (-1)^n*sum {k = 1..n} T(n,k)*f^(n-k)/((1+x)^n*f^(2n+1)).

A075857.name: Least common multiple of totient and cototient of n.

A075859.name: a(n) = n concatenated with n 1's and n.
